Overview

This assignment is focused on fitting and comparing regression models. Your task is to fit 9 polynomial models from degree 1 (linear relationship) to degree 9 (a 9th degree polynomial). You will interpret behavior through analyzing the coefficient estimates and by visualizing predictions from the models. You must select the best performing model and you will do so several different ways. You will first consider performance on the training set alone, then use a single train/test split, and finally using 5-fold cross-validation.

You will work with 3 different data sets, but all 3 data sets were generated from the same data generating process. These 3 different versions of the data will allow you consider the influence of sample size (low vs high) and uncontrollable variation or noise (low vs high) on the model selection process.

The above print out can work, but it is not the best way to organize the data. The above format is known as wide-format since the table is wide relative to the observations. The column names (variables) are critical for distinguishing one model from the other! We are thus using the column names to represent variable and the value! Such an organizational format is common, especially in presenting results, but it is not recommended because it limits how we can manipulate the data. Instead, it is better to use a TIDY format where the columns are distinct variables, rows are observations, and each cell of the table contains a single value. We can force the above wide-format object into a tidy-format by reshaping to long-format. However, lets create the long-format results from scratch to see how to organize data in this style.

The code chunk below creates a long-format data set where one row corresponds to the result of a single model. Two columns are created, poly_degree, denotes the models polynomial degree and RMSE the RMSE value for that model.

results_fit_lf <- tibble::tibble(
  poly_degree = 1:9,
  RMSE = c(modelr::rmse(fit_lm_1, df_low_high),
           modelr::rmse(fit_lm_2, df_low_high),
           modelr::rmse(fit_lm_3, df_low_high),
           modelr::rmse(fit_lm_4, df_low_high),
           modelr::rmse(fit_lm_5, df_low_high),
           modelr::rmse(fit_lm_6, df_low_high),
           modelr::rmse(fit_lm_7, df_low_high),
           modelr::rmse(fit_lm_8, df_low_high),
           modelr::rmse(fit_lm_9, df_low_high))
)

Later in the semester we will introduce functional programming techniques that apply a function in an iterative manner. For now, lets see how such techniques can streamline the programming task of organizing the results into a TIDY long-format tibble. The code chunk below uses the purrr library (which is loaded via tidyverse) to apply the modelr::rmse() function to all models. 1g)

Some of the coefficients are present in all three models displayed in the figure from Problem 1f), while a few of the coefficients are only present in one of the models. Lets look closely at the previous figure to try and interpret the model behavior.

Are the coefficient estimates similar for those coefficients present in at least 2 of the models visualized in the previous figure?

Is the level or amount of uncertainty associated with the coefficients consistent across the three models?

SOLUTION

The quadratic feature (the input squared) is one of the more interesting features to look at in the previous figure. The quadratic model has a statistically significant positive quadratic feature. The 6th degree and 9th degree polynomials do not consider the quadratic feature to be statistically significant. However, the 6th degree polynomial has a negative value for the estimate. This shows that by adding features to a model, a features coefficient sign can flip! There is a similar phenomena with the linear feature (the input itself). The quadratic feature considers the linear feature to be statistically significantly positive, while the other two models do not think this feature is statistically significant. The linear features coefficient estimate is negative (6th degree) or close to zero (9th degree) for the other two models.

The easy take away from the coefficient plot is that the 9th degree polynomial has very uncertain coefficients. This is especially apparent for the 4th degree feature. The uncertainty interval spans roughly -40 to +20.

The seq() function is a simple way to create a vector from a lower bound to an upper bound. You previously used two performance metrics to identify the best model. How would you describe the predictive trends associated with the best performing model? Do the trends seem consistent with the training set?

SOLUTION

The best performing model was identified to be the 9th degree polynomial, regardless of the performance metric. However, we assessed the performance only on the training set. The performance therefore only considered if the model matched the data used to fit the models. The predictions we created, goes beyond the training set and examines the model behavior at input values not present in the training data. We are asking the models what happens in between the training data. We are therefore diving deeper into the models implied behavior.

The predictive trends associated with the most complex models show a peak near x = 2 in the right side of the each facet. This peak is easiest to see with the training set identified best model, the 9th degree polynomial. Even though this model fits the training data better than any other model, this model thinks the trend increases sharply and then turns around and rapidly decreases at the highest input value. This peak has a predicted trend over 10x larger than most of the responses in the training set! This behavior occurs in an interval with very little data. Thus, we have no way of knowing if such behavior is real or is just an artifact of the model. Such artifacts can be an indication that the model is overfit to the training data. It is finding wiggles and persisting those wiggles to sparsely populated intervals.

The predictions identified behavior that is not present in the training set because we do not have any observations in that interval to backup such behavior! We therefore need some other way to identify if such complexity is real or not!

The random seed is specified for you with the set.seed() function in the code chunk below. This ensures that the data splitting is reproducible. You will therefore get the same split every time you run the code chunk below. Please note, you must run the entire code chunk to ensure reproducibility.

You must then use id_train to slice the training set from df_low_high and slice all except the id_train indices to create the hold-out test set. The training set is df_train and the hold-out test set is df_holdout in the code chunk below.

We have 40 observations in total. The 80/20 train/test split means we will use 32 training points and 8 test (validation) hold-out points.

4c)

The caret package requires that we specify a primary performance metric of interest, even though it will calculate several performance metrics for us. Please remember that the response is a continuous variable.

You must select a primary performance metric to use to compare the models. Specify an appropriate metric to use for this modeling task. NOTE: Not all of the listed performance metrics above are relevant to regression problems!

SOLUTION

We need to use a performance metric associated with regression. Thus, we can choose RMSE, MAE, or Rsquared from the set of choices above. We are using 5 fold cross-validation and thus each folds holdout test set contains 20% of the data. We have 40 rows and so 20% corresponds to just 8 observations in the test set. For that reason, I want to focus on an error metric rather than the general relationship between the model and the observations. There are less than 10 observations and so the Rsquared calculations can be rather unstable within the folds. You may receive full credit for selecting RMSE or MAE in this problem.

my_metric <- 'RMSE'

6d)

The df_low_high and df_high_high data have the same noise level, but different sample sizes.

Did the resampling scheme identify the same model as the best model for the two sample size cases? Did the models identified to be poor for the low sample size case remain poor for the high sample size case?

SOLUTION

No! A smaller sample size identified the simpler cubic model as the best performing model. The larger sample size case identified more complex models as performing better. However, the most complex 9th degree polynomials was ruled out regardless of sample size.

6e)

You have executed a model selection task under varying levels of noise and sample sizes. Your goal was to select the best model from a candidate set of varying levels of complexity.

What do you think the impact is between sample size and noise level on the ability to identify complex behavior?

SOLUTION

Noisy data makes it difficult to identify complex patterns. We are not sure if the relationship is real or is fake due to the high amount of random and uncontrollable noise. Models trained with small sample sizes are especially susceptible to noise, which is why the resampling scheme identified simpler models as being better. When we have larger sample sizes, we can be more confident in the trends simply because we have more data. As we will learn later in the semester, models are trying to find the average response. More samples means we are more confident in the average. Essentially, more data allows us to see the signal through the noise. The resampling scheme is then capable of picking up more complicated patterns and to be confident those patterns are real. Thus, if we have noisy data, we need higher sample sizes to be confident the complexity is real and not random scatter.

Conversely, if the noise is low then it is easier to identify complex patterns. We do not need as many samples because we have a higher resolution snapshot of the process.

In summary, we are capable of finding complex patterns if we have either low noise data or large sample sizes. Small sample sizes of highly noise data makes it easy for complex models to overfit the training data. Resampling schemes identify simpler models because the noise makes us not trust the complex models, even if complex patterns truly exist.
